{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11647990]] Wikidata name: Kinkaku-ji arson incident [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 04:12, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} On 2 July 1950, at 2:30 am, the pavilion was burned down<ref name="whe1">{{cite web |last1=Cartwright |first1=Mark |title=Kinkakuji |url=https://www.worldhistory.org/Kinkakuji/ |website=World History Encyclopedia |publisher=UNESCO |access-date=23 March 2021]]</ref> by a 22-year-old novice monk, Hayashi Yoken ({{ill|Kinkaku-ji arson incident|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinkaku-ji arson incident|qq=}} ), who then attempted suicide on the Daimon-ji hill behind the building. He survived, and was subsequently taken into custody. The monk was sentenced to seven years in prison, but was released because of mental illnesses ([[:en:persecution complex|persecution complex]] and [[:en:schizophrenia|schizophrenia]]) on 29 September 1955; he died of [[:en:tuberculosis|tuberculosis]] in March 1956.<ref><nowiki>{{cite book|author=Albert Borowitz|title=Terrorism for self-glorification: the Herostratos syndrome|url=</nowiki>https://archive.org/details/terrorismforself0000boro%7Curl-access=registration%7Caccess-date=1 July 2011|year=2005|publisher=Kent State University Press|isbn=978-0-87338-818-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/terrorismforself0000boro/page/49 49]–62]] See: [[:en:Herostratos syndrome|Herostratos syndrome]]</ref> During the fire, the original statue of Ashikaga Yoshimitsu was lost to the flames (now restored). A fictionalized version of these events is at the center of [[:en:Yukio Mishima|Yukio Mishima]]'s 1956 book ''[[:en:The Temple of the Golden Pavilion|The Temple of the Golden Pavilion]]'',<ref name="orientalarch"/> and another in the ballet ''[[:en:RAkU (ballet)| RAkU]]''.
{{translated page|ja|金閣寺放火事件|version=104521219|comment=Imported full ja history}}
